
===================================
📌 1. Finglish Version (Persian Latin Script)
===================================

📖 **Tashrih:**
    Dastoor `evince-previewer` baraye pish-namayesh file-haye PDF va digar format-haye moshabeh be kar miravad. In dastoor asosan baraye estefade dar barname-haye digar (mesle file manager-ha) tarrahi shodeh ast ta betonand pish-namayesh-haye sari' az file-ha ra namayesh dahand.

⚙️ **Gozine-ha:**
    🔹 `--embed`  --> 📦 Barname ra dar yek panjareye digar ja midahad. (Asosan baraye developers)
    🔹 `--page=NUMBER`  --> 📄 Safheye moshakhas shodeh ra namayesh midahad.
    🔹 `--display=DISPLAY` --> 🖥️ Namayesh dar yek X display-e khass. (Agar chand monitor darid)

🛠 **Mesal-ha:**

    $ evince-previewer file.pdf

    🔹  File PDF `file.pdf` ra pish-namayesh midahad.

    $ evince-previewer --page=5 file.pdf

    🔹  File PDF `file.pdf` ra baz mikonad va be safheye 5 miravad.

✅ **Mesal sade:**

    $ evince-previewer document.pdf &

    🔹 `document.pdf` ra dar pishnamayesh evince baz mikonad va be shoma ejaze midahad ke dar terminal dastoorat digari ra niz ejra konid. `&` yani dastoor dar paszamine ejra shavad.

===================================
📌 2. English Version
===================================

📖 **Description:**
    The `evince-previewer` command is used to preview PDF files and other similar formats. It's primarily designed for use within other applications (like file managers) to provide quick file previews.

⚙️ **Options:**
    🔹 `--embed`  --> 📦 Embeds the application into another window. (Mainly for developers)
    🔹 `--page=NUMBER`  --> 📄 Displays a specific page number.
    🔹 `--display=DISPLAY` --> 🖥️ Displays on a specific X display (if you have multiple monitors).

🛠 **Examples:**

    $ evince-previewer file.pdf

    🔹  Previews the PDF file `file.pdf`.

    $ evince-previewer --page=5 file.pdf

    🔹  Opens the PDF file `file.pdf` and navigates to page 5.

✅ **Simple Example:**

    $ evince-previewer document.pdf &

    🔹 Opens `document.pdf` in the evince previewer and allows you to execute other commands in the terminal. The `&` means the command runs in the background.
